    "summary": "Operation Desert Storm, the coalition military offensive to liberate Kuwait from Iraqi occupation, began on January 17, 1991 with an air campaign that targeted Iraqi military infrastructure, communications, and air defenses. For thirty-eight days, coalition aircraft flew over 100,000 sorties, systematically degrading Iraqi military capabilities before the ground offensive began. The air campaign employed precision-guided munitions extensively, marking a new era of so-called smart warfare, though a substantial proportion of bombs used were still unguided.\n\nThe ground war, launched on February 24, 1991, lasted only 100 hours. Coalition forces employed a sweeping flanking maneuver, sending heavy armored units far to the west of Iraq's prepared defensive positions before cutting east to encircle the Iraqi army in Kuwait. Iraqi forces were routed, with thousands surrendering and Kuwait City liberated within days. President George H.W. Bush declared a ceasefire on February 28, 1991. The coalition suffered fewer than 300 combat deaths while Iraqi military casualties were estimated in the tens of thousands. Saddam Hussein's regime survived the war, however, and the decision not to march on Baghdad left unresolved tensions that shaped the region for the next decade and provided the context for the 2003 Iraq War.",
